-webflow/assets/integrations/README.md:\n  Line 21: This README documents the code-bearing folder `.opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/webflow/integrations` so operators can understand its role without opening every source file first. It follows the sk-doc skill README structure while staying focused on code navigation.\n\n  Line 25: Use this file to identify the folder boundary, the likely verification path, and the local source files that need sk-code conventions. Keep behavior details in source comments and higher-level workflow details in the owning `SKILL.md`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/assets/animation/playbook_entries.md:\n  Line 22: These entries can be lifted into `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/motion_dev_and_animation_regression/` or used standalone. They expand Packet 1's MR-001 through MR-004 scenarios with API context from `references/animation/`.\n\n  Line 35: Create a sandboxed Webflow-style Motion smoke page that imports animate, inView, and spring from a pinned motion CDN URL. Run it in Chrome, verify exports are functions, run one animate() call, trigger one inView() callback, and return PASS/FAIL with console evidence.\n\n  Line 59: Audit the repo for Motion CDN URLs. Confirm no production Motion URL uses @latest, record the pinned version(s), and verify the pinned ESM bundle exposes animate, inView, scroll, and motionValue for the testimonial slider pattern.\n\n  Line 81: Enable prefers-reduced-motion: reduce in Chrome DevTools, exercise the Motion testimonial slider and nav dropdown, and verify transform-heavy movement is disabled, shortened to instant state changes, or replaced with opacity-only changes. Return PASS/FAIL with before/after evidence.\n\n  Line 104: Record baseline videos for the Motion nav dropdown open/close flow and testimonial slider next/previous/drag flow. Compare the run against the current baseline, note any visual drift, console errors, or timing regressions, and return PASS/FAIL with artifact paths.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/assets/animation/install_card.md:\n  Line 32: Pinned examples in this card use `12.38.0`, the latest stable package version observed during authoring on 2026-05-05. Recheck the package before future upgrades; never copy `@latest` into production snippets. Motion's quick start recommends replacing `latest` with a concrete version (Source: https://motion.dev/docs/quick-start; version cross-check: https://motion.dev/).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/assets/animation/snippets/README.md:\n  Line 21: This README documents the code-bearing folder `.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/assets/animation/snippets` so operators can understand its role without opening every source file first. It follows the sk-doc skill README structure while staying focused on code navigation.\n\n  Line 25: Use this file to identify the folder boundary, the likely verification path, and the local source files that need sk-code conventions. Keep behavior details in source comments and higher-level workflow details in the owning `SKILL.md`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/assets/webflow_verification_checklist.md:\n  Line 22: **The Iron Law**: Evidence in browser before claims, always. This checklist ensures all claims are backed by actual browser testing evidence.\n\n  Line 26: Use this checklist BEFORE claiming any work is complete, fixed, or working. Complete all applicable sections before making completion claims.\n\n  Line 221: errors. Mobile viewport transitions smooth.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/README.md:\n  Line 3: description: Read-only WEBFLOW surface evidence for the sk-code hub — frontend standards, implementation and performance patterns, CDN deployment, browser debug/verify. Bundled alongside a workflow mode; never a primary.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/SKILL.md:\n  Line 16: **Domain evidence** and shared workflow doctrine for browser/Webflow frontend work. This surface owns the implement -> debug -> verify phases through the workflow references below, and acts on the evidence gathered here when the hub detects a Webflow surface. Detection markers: `src/2_javascript`, `webflow`, `--vw-` custom properties, CDN-delivered client scripts.\n\n  Line 222: - **CDN runtime reality.** Client scripts ship over a CDN with cache lag; treat every deploy as versioned and verify the minified runtime, not just the source. See `references/deployment/minification_guide/overview_terser_and_patterns.md` and `references/verification/verification_workflows/gate_and_automated_options.md`.\n\n  Line 223: - **Interaction-gated loading.** Heavy vendors (HLS.js, FilePond, Swiper) load on interaction/visibility, never eagerly. See `references/performance/interaction_gated_loading.md` and `references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/README.md:\n  Line 35: Implementation can produce code that is behaviorally close but still not shippable: a forbidden comment label, a missing authoring checklist, stale generated output, a style violation, or a P0 quality defect that verification would not explain well. The quality mode closes that gap before final evidence is collected.\n\n  Line 39: `code-quality` consumes the parent `sk-code` surface detection, loads the required quality checklist, selects an OpenCode authoring checklist by target path when needed, runs the comment-hygiene checker per modified file, and applies P0/P1/P2 author checks. It can edit existing scoped files to fix gate failures. It does not create new files, dispatch tasks, or produce formal review reports.\n\n  Line 47: **Step 2: Load the right checklist.** The mode always loads [`assets/code_quality_checklist.md`](assets/code_quality_checklist/overview_header_and_comments.md). For `.opencode/` targets, it also loads the matching checklist under [`assets/checklists/`](../code-opencode/assets/checklists/).\n\n  Line 51: **Step 4: Fix or hand back.** Fix in-place quality failures with `Edit`. Hand broader implementation to the surface skill (`code-webflow` / `code-opencode`), root-cause failures to the surface's debugging workflow (`workflow_debug.md`), and final evidence to the surface's verification workflow (`workflow_verify.md`).\n\n  Line 57: The mode sits between implementation and verification. It reads the changed files, resolves surface identity from shared router references, applies the right checklist family, runs comment hygiene, and checks P0/P1/P2 status. P0 blocks completion. P1 is fixed unless the user accepts a documented risk. P2 is fixed when cheap or explicitly deferred with a reason.\n\n  Line 61: OpenCode authoring targets route to specific checklists: skills, agents, commands, spec folders, MCP servers, language files, and config each have their own checklist. Webflow/frontend work uses the code quality checklist and shared universal standards.\n\n  Line 65: This mode can edit already-scoped files because author-side quality correction is part of implementation. It cannot write new files and cannot dispatch subagents. Findings-only review belongs to `code-review`.\n\n  Line 73: Use it when a change is already written and needs standards enforcement before final verification: skill authoring, script changes, config changes, frontend quality, comment hygiene, or stale generated-output checks. Skip it when the task is to build new behavior, debug a failing symptom, verify non-mutating evidence, or review without editing.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:\n  Line 8: First release of the `webflow` surface packet. The Webflow frontend evidence that previously lived scattered across the workflow modes (`code-implement/references/webflow/` + `assets/webflow/`, `code-debug/references/webflow-debugging/`, `code-verify/references/webflow-verification/`, `shared/references/webflow-shared/`) is now consolidated under one read-only surface packet on the sk-code hub's surface axis.\n\n  Line 19: This packet is `packetKind: surface`, `backendKind: evidence-base`, read-only (`toolSurface` ⊆ {Read, Bash, Grep, Glob}), and advisor-invisible (`routingClass: metadata`). It is reached only by the hub bundling it alongside a workflow mode via `routerPolicy.outcomes.surfaceBundle`; it never routes as a primary and mutates nothing.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/assets/webflow_debugging_checklist.md:\n  Line 22: Ensures thorough investigation before attempting fixes. Follow phases in order: Investigation → Pattern Analysis → Hypothesis Testing → Implementation.\n\n  Line 26: Use this checklist for ANY frontend technical issue. Complete all applicable phases sequentially before moving to implementation.\n\n  Line 222: **Remember:** Find root cause BEFORE fixing. Symptom fixes are failure.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/assets/patterns/README.md:\n  Line 21: This README documents the code-bearing folder `.opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/webflow/patterns` so operators can understand its role without opening every source file first. It follows the sk-doc skill README structure while staying focused on code navigation.\n\n  Line 25: Use this file to identify the folder boundary, the likely verification path, and the local source files that need sk-code conventions. Keep behavior details in source comments and higher-level workflow details in the owning `SKILL.md`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:\n  Line 8: First release of the `quality` workflow mode on the `sk-code` hub. Born in the parent-hub refactor that collapsed sk-code from eight sub-skills to four surface-primary packets, the author-side quality gate is now a single mode child that runs after the surface skill (`code-webflow` / `code-opencode`) implements changes and before the surface's verification workflow or done-claim.\n\n  Line 21: This mode consumes the parent `sk-code` surface detection, edits only files the surface skill already changed to clear gate failures, creates no new files, and dispatches no subagents. Findings-first review lives in `code-review`; spec-folder authoring lives in `system-spec-kit`. The packet is currently at 1.0.0.1 following a post-establishment metadata sweep with no behavior change.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 3: Routing-recall corpus for the `code-webflow` surface. These scenarios exercise the machine-readable intent signals and resource map in the skill router without requiring a root scenario index table.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/interaction_gated_loading.md:\n  Line 49: **Rule:** Prefer the latest safe trigger. If a feature is only needed after intent is clear, do not initialize it on page load.\n\n  Line 95: 1. Run Lighthouse mobile 3x in Incognito and use the median.\n\n  Line 96: 2. Compare TBT and long-task count before first interaction.\n\n  Line 97: 3. Check first-use latency for the gated feature.\n\n  Line 98: 4. Confirm INP does not regress on the interaction path.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v4.0.0.0.md:\n  Line 8: sk-code converted from a flat two-axis skill into a nested parent hub with 5 mode packets (implement, quality, debug, verify, review) over a shared surface-detection router; folds the review doctrine in as the code-review mode. Scaffold phase - packets are skeletons; content relocation follows.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/webflow_constraints.md:\n  Line 25: Webflow's platform imposes specific limitations on performance optimization. Understanding these constraints prevents wasted effort on impossible optimizations and helps focus on what IS controllable.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/plugins_and_hooks/post_edit_quality_router.md:\n  Line 237: These references are unstable and will rot. Replace each with the durable WHY.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 9: Type-1 resource-recall scenarios for the deterministic skill-benchmark (Lane C, router mode). code-quality routes primarily by TARGET PATH — verified by its own unit test — and its parent-to-child discoverability is the hub `quality` signal. This playbook exercises the one thin prompt-intent `QUALITY` route so the harness can score its single routable checklist in Mode-A.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/resource_loading.md:\n  Line 25: Resource loading optimization uses browser hints to prioritize critical resources and defer non-essential ones. This improves Core Web Vitals, particularly LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) and FID (First Input Delay).\n\n  Line 67: **Rule:** When in doubt, include `crossorigin`. It's safer to over-specify.\n\n  Line 102: Performs DNS lookup only (no TCP/TLS). Lower priority than preconnect, used for resources that may be needed later.\n\n  Line 130: Downloads high-priority resources for the current page with elevated priority. Browser fetches immediately regardless of discovery order.\n\n  Line 152: **Important:** The `as` attribute is required. Without it, the browser downloads the resource twice.\n\n  Line 172: > **Cross-stack motion.dev reference**: For canonical motion.dev install patterns (CDN module + legacy global + npm), version-pin policy, and verification snippets that apply across stacks (not just Webflow), see [`../animation/integration_patterns.md`](../animation/integration_patterns.md) and [`../../assets/animation/install_card.md`](../../assets/animation/install_card.md). The Webflow preload pattern above remains the authoritative source for Webflow-CDN-specific resource loading.\n\n  Line 186: Downloads resources for future navigation during idle time. Lower priority than preload.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/README.md:\n  Line 35: An ad-hoc review reads the diff once and reports whatever the reviewer happened to notice. Security gaps slip through. Correctness bugs get a mention but no evidence. A single generic checklist cannot capture a specific stack's idioms, build and test commands, but a per-stack reviewer would need rebuilding for every language. Without a fixed output shape, downstream automation cannot tell an approval from a request for changes.\n\n  Line 37: The `code-review` mode (of the sk-code family) fixes this. It pairs a stack-agnostic baseline that always enforces security and correctness minimums with surface-specific standards loaded through sk-code, and it ends every review with one exact status line a gate can parse.\n\n  Line 41: The `code-review` mode (of the sk-code family) is the single-pass review baseline for the `@review` agent. It classifies every finding as P0 (blocking, blocks merge), P1 (required, fix before merge) or P2 (suggestion, optional), ordered by severity with file:line evidence on P0 and P1 findings. It is read-only on the target: it reports findings and never edits the code under review.\n\n  Line 49: **Step 1: Invoke it.** Gate 2 routing fires on review keywords, or you dispatch the `@review` agent. The dispatcher prepends `CODE-REVIEW` as the first line of the rendered prompt so the reviewer knows it is operating as the baseline.\n\n  Line 59: **Step 2: Read the output contract.** Every review follows the same shape. Findings come before summary. Security and correctness checks run first. The review ends with one exact status line.\n\n  Line 94: The final line is always exactly one of `Review status: APPROVED`, `Review status: REQUESTED_CHANGES` or `Review status: COMMENTED`, with no trailing whitespace. Downstream automation parses it by exact string match.\n\n  Line 102: Findings-first means the review runs security and correctness checks before anything else. After those come quality and performance, then architecture (KISS, DRY, SOLID) and finally removal opportunities. This order keeps the blocking risks visible at the top where a merge decision needs them.\n\n  Line 108: P0 is a blocker: exploitable security issues, auth bypass or destructive data loss. A P0 blocks merge. P1 is required: correctness bugs, spec mismatches or must-fix gate issues that need resolution before merge. P2 is a suggestion: non-blocking improvements, documentation polish or style follow-ups that are optional.\n\n  Line 110: Every P0 and P1 finding must include a concrete file:line citation. P2 findings should include specific evidence when available.\n\n  Line 114: The baseline minimums from the `code-review` mode are always enforced and never relaxed by surface guidance. Security and correctness checks are non-negotiable. When a code surface is detected, `sk-code` supplies the surface's style conventions, build commands and test commands, which override the baseline's generic guidance on those topics.\n\n  Line 116: When the surface is unknown, the review runs baseline-only and discloses the uncertainty. When baseline and surface guidance conflict in a way that cannot be resolved, the reviewer escalates instead of guessing.\n\n  Line 120: All findings publish in one message with a next-action prompt. Findings never drip across multiple turns. The reviewer collects everything, orders by severity and emits the full report, then waits for explicit direction before any follow-up.\n\n  Line 124: Two optional gates reduce redundant work. The content-hash dedup gate skips a re-review when the diff has not changed since the last one, writing a signature into `.opencode/.code-review-cache/`. The minimum-evidence gate skips full review for trivially small diffs when enabled through `SK_CODE_REVIEW_MIN_CHANGED_LINES`, but it never skips diffs that touch auth, config, persistence, dependencies, sandboxing or public-facing response paths. Both gates are opt-in and never change the baseline findings. The optional `SK_CODE_REVIEW_DEPTH=lite|full|ultra` alias names and persists this routing for a session: `ultra` biases toward the deep-dive reference set, `lite` maps to the conservative skip, and neither relaxes the security and correctness floor.\n\n  Line 132: Reach for the `code-review` mode (of the sk-code family) when you want severity-ranked findings with file:line evidence before merging, when a gate workflow dispatches `@review` for pre-commit validation or when you need a read-only security and correctness pass with a machine-readable verdict. Skip it for feature implementation without review intent, for pure documentation edits or for git-only tasks that carry no code-quality evaluation.\n\n  Line 142: The `code-review` mode and deep-review share `references/review_core.md`, so P0, P1 and P2 mean the same thing in both workflows. The boundary is single-pass versus iterative. Use `code-review` when you want one report. Use deep-review when the scope demands multiple passes with tracked convergence.\n\n  Line 163: A: The findings are the blocking pieces of the review. A merge decision depends on them. Putting them first puts the evidence where the reviewer and the automation both reach for it.\n\n  Line 167: A: Baseline-only when sk-code cannot detect the code surface or returns UNKNOWN. In that case the review enforces security and correctness minimums and discloses the gap. When a surface is detected, the review loads the surface's style, build and test standards on top.\n\n  Line 171: A: The `code-review` mode is the single-pass baseline. One report, one status line, next action decided by a human. deep-review adds iterative passes, JSONL state tracking, deltas between iterations and autonomous convergence. Both use the same severity taxonomy and evidence rules from `references/review_core.md`.\n\n  Line 175: A: The surface skills (`code-webflow` / `code-opencode`) apply fixes and own the implement → debug → verify workflow doctrine, and `code-quality` owns author-side gates. The `code-review` mode consumes surface evidence as the review layer. It owns the review workflow, the severity classification and the output contract.\n\n  Line 179: A: Downstream automation reads the final line by exact string match to decide whether to block a merge, request changes or pass. The three values are the contract. No variation is accepted.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview_header_and_comments.md:\n  Line 22: Validate code against style standards before claiming implementation is complete. This checklist ensures consistent, maintainable code across the codebase.\n\n  Line 175: > **Cross-stack motion.dev reference**: For motion.dev API surface, decision matrix, and integration patterns that apply across stacks (not just Webflow), see [`../../../code-webflow/references/animation/quick_start.md`](../../../code-webflow/references/animation/quick_start.md) and the documents in [`../../code-webflow/references/animation`](../../code-webflow/references/animation). The MOTION constraint above remains a Webflow-CDN-specific platform marker.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/cwv_remediation.md:\n  Line 57: **Why it matters:** If the hero animation fails or takes too long, users see a blank page indefinitely. The safety timeout guarantees page visibility after a maximum wait time.\n\n  Line 70: > **Cross-stack motion.dev reference**: For Motion performance and fallback guidance that applies beyond this Webflow CWV timeout pattern, see [`../animation/performance_and_pitfalls.md`](../animation/performance_and_pitfalls.md). The timeout hierarchy here remains the Webflow-specific CWV remediation contract.\n\n  Line 72: **The chain:** Each hero script has its own timeout (1s for libraries, 2s for images). The safety timeout is the last-resort guarantee that fires independently of hero scripts.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/benchmark/router_mode_a/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 3: > Rendered from report.json (do not hand-edit). Scoring: `mode-a-router-replay` · trace mode: `router`.\n\n  Line 46: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode. Advisory signals: mode precision unscored; relative ranking unscored (no advisor probe or no rank-below gold); route gold rows 0; telemetry missing n/a (0/0); route misses n/a (0/0); alias misses n/a (0/0); bundle misses n/a (0/0); recipe misses n/a (0/0).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.4.0.0.md:\n  Line 6: This release folds the sk-code slice of the packet 146 ponytail-based refinement into the code-work skill — reusable restraint teachings transplanted from an external reference and added on top of the existing routing without changing surface precedence or the Iron Law. The theme is doing the least that is still correct: before writing new code the implementer now walks a short restraint ladder, builds the simplest correct version instead of stalling on a scope question, names a deliberate shortcut so it reads as intent rather than ignorance, and a new validator keeps the surface routing map honest against what is actually on disk.\n\n  Line 14: Three additions land in the always-loaded universal references plus one new verification script. None of them change surface detection, surface precedence (OPENCODE over WEBFLOW over UNKNOWN), or the Iron Law; they sit after routing as pre-write reflexes and one structural check.\n\n  Line 18: An agent with a green light to implement tended to reach for a custom solution first. A new roughly thirteen-line Design Restraint Ladder in the always-loaded `references/universal/code_quality_standards.md` makes the agent climb from least to most code before writing: does this need to exist at all (YAGNI), then a standard-library primitive, a native platform or runtime feature, an already-installed dependency, a one-line expression, and only then a minimal custom implementation. It is a post-read reflex that runs AFTER surface and intent routing, so it consumes the detected surface but changes neither surface precedence nor the Iron Law (Phase 3 verification is still required). The ladder is gated to the Phase 0 to Phase 1 transition in `references/phase_detection.md` — the 0 to 1 gate now requires that, for implementation intent, the laziest viable rung has been selected — and it is named in the SKILL.md Phase Overview so the implementer meets it before the first line of new code.\n\n  Line 24: A restraint ladder can backfire into paralysis: an agent that spots a possibly unnecessary requirement might stop and ask rather than ship. A new §4 ALWAYS bullet in `SKILL.md` closes that gap. The implementer builds the simplest correct implementation of the stated requirement and does not stall. When part of the requirement looks unnecessary, it implements the requirement as specified AND raises a scope-amendment recommendation in the same response — it never silently cuts scope (SCOPE-LOCK still holds) and never blocks solely to ask when a safe minimal version already satisfies the requirement.\n\n  Line 30: When a simplification is deliberate — a known shortcut chosen on purpose, not an oversight — it should read as intent. A new convention in `references/universal/code_style_guide.md` §4 introduces a neutral `ceiling:` comment that names the shortcut, its known ceiling, and the upgrade path or trigger. It is a durable WHY, not a brand or tool prefix (a brand prefix reads as a perishable, cargo-cult label), and it is explicitly NOT added to the comment-hygiene checker's allowed-pattern list — it already passes because it carries no forbidden id, and allow-listing it would let a forbidden id on the same line slip through. This is the producer-side companion to the reviewer-side downgrade rule shipped in sk-code-review v1.4.0.0.\n\n  Line 36: The smart router declares each surface in a `STACK_FOLDERS` map and then loads that surface's patterns from `references/<surface>/` and `assets/<surface>/`. If a declared surface had no folders, or a surface-shaped folder existed with no declaration, the router would silently load nothing or drift from its documented contract with no warning. A new `assets/scripts/verify_stack_folders.py` parses the `STACK_FOLDERS` literal out of SKILL.md and asserts that every declared surface resolves to both an on-disk references folder and an assets folder, and that no orphan surface folder exists undeclared in either the `references/` or the `assets/` tree (the shared `universal/` material and the `scripts/` tooling directory are exempt by design). It exits non-zero with a per-problem report when the declaration and the folders disagree.\n\n  Line 53: No migration required. The ladder, the anti-stall rule, and the `ceiling:` convention are additive guidance that change how the implementer approaches new code, not the surface routing or the verification contract. The new validator is a standalone check; run `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/scripts/verify_stack_folders.py` to confirm every declared surface resolves to real folders.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/third_party.md:\n  Line 25: Third-party scripts (analytics, tag managers, consent) often block the main thread and degrade Core Web Vitals. This guide covers deferral patterns to minimize their performance impact while maintaining functionality.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/benchmark/router_mode_a/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 3: > Rendered from report.json (do not hand-edit). Scoring: `mode-a-router-replay` · trace mode: `router`.\n\n  Line 71: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode. Advisory signals: mode precision unscored; relative ranking unscored (no advisor probe or no rank-below gold); route gold rows 0; telemetry missing n/a (0/0); route misses n/a (0/0); alias misses n/a (0/0); bundle misses n/a (0/0); recipe misses n/a (0/0).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/routing_disambiguation/mixed_marker_ambiguity.md:\n  Line 16: Either is acceptable IF the chosen behavior is documented in SKILL.md. What is NOT acceptable: silently picking one without surfacing the conflict.\n\n  Line 18: > **Note**: This scenario was the validation target for F-NEW-001 from the 2026-05-04 deep-review iteration. SKILL.md smart router pseudocode previously had a precedence bug (WEBFLOW markers capturing OPENCODE-targeted prompts; unconditional `SURFACE=\"UNKNOWN\"` overwriting prior matches). **REMEDIATED 2026-05-04**: pseudocode restructured with explicit `if/elif/else` precedence — OPENCODE target/CWD wins over WEBFLOW markers. This scenario now exercises the documented precedence (Outcome A).\n\n  Line 35: **Outcome A (documented precedence)**: SKILL.md states OPENCODE target path overrides WEBFLOW library marker. sk-code reports `SURFACE: OPENCODE`, `LANGUAGE: JAVASCRIPT`, loads `code-opencode/references/javascript/*` + shared. Does NOT load `code-webflow/references/*`.\n\n  Line 39: **Unacceptable**: Silent choice (e.g. WEBFLOW silently wins because of marker order in pseudocode) without documenting the precedence.\n\n  Line 45: 1. SKILL.md is at HEAD-of-main.\n\n  Line 47: 3. Either remediation for F-NEW-001 has landed (then test for Outcome A) OR has not (then test for either A or B; document which behavior the AI exhibits).\n\n  Line 51: 1. Invoke sk-code with the prompt.\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"^[^#\\n].*[.!?]\\s+[A-Z].*[.!?]$","time":{"start":1783921511579,"end":1783921511590}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00202cee44cb2fed016a547b6741288191bdf4d677132b4220"}},"id":"prt_f5a020c07001OCTnSyhmIYmzLK","sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","messageID":"msg_f5a01d8d1001c6NAefm0Cfvw2Z"}}
