{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1783921521776,"sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","part":{"id":"prt_f5a02346f001OCUQnpV7VkQUeX","messageID":"msg_f5a0211520013lygw3ydBKV8sp","sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921533681,"sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ldrF2oimJGdoXoLc9pDBP58R","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_debug.md","offset":1,"limit":50},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_debug.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Workflow Reference - Debugging\n3: description: Shared debugging workflow doctrine for sk-code — root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure, consumed by every surface packet.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"sk-code debugging workflow\"\n6:   - \"debug workflow doctrine\"\n7:   - \"root-cause diagnosis\"\n8:   - \"scoped repair workflow\"\n9: importance_tier: important\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.0.0.1\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Workflow Reference - Debugging\n15: \n16: Shared debugging workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure appears. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Debugging is the controlled experiment phase. It reproduces or tightly characterizes the symptom, captures exact evidence, traces the symptom backward to a source cause, applies one-cause fixes, and sends the result back through quality and verification.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Diagnosing a failing test, build failure, runtime exception, console error, broken interaction, layout regression, command failure, or inconsistent runtime behavior.\n29: - Recovering from failed implementation, failed quality, failed verification, or a concrete regression.\n30: - Tracing a symptom backward before changing code.\n31: - Applying a minimal bug fix to already-scoped files after the root cause is identified.\n32: - Dispatching a bounded parallel investigation when the search space is broad but the symptom is concrete.\n33: - Enforcing the three-strike escalation rule after repeated failed fixes for the same symptom.\n34: \n35: ### When Not to Use\n36: \n37: - The work is planned implementation or refactoring without a failing symptom; use the implementation phase.\n38: - The work is an author-side quality gate with no concrete failing behavior; use the quality phase.\n39: - The work is final non-mutating evidence after a fix; use the verification phase.\n40: - The user wants findings-first review output rather than author-side repair.\n41: - The task is documentation-only prose with no failing behavior.\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## 2. WORKFLOW\n46: \n47: ### Debug Loop\n48: \n49: 1. Resolve the active surface and lifecycle phase through shared references. If the surface is unknown, ask for runtime and verification commands before changing code.\n50: 2. Reproduce the symptom. If it cannot be reproduced, collect the exact command, logs, inputs, state, or interaction steps needed to narrow it.\n\n(Showing lines 1-50 of 121. Use offset=51 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Debugging\ndescription: Shared debugging workflow doctrine for sk-code — root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure, consumed by every surface packet.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code debugging workflow\"\n  - \"debug workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"root-cause diagnosis\"\n  - \"scoped repair workflow\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.1\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Debugging\n\nShared debugging workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure appears. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_debug.md","text":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Debugging\ndescription: Shared debugging workflow doctrine for sk-code — root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure, consumed by every surface packet.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code debugging workflow\"\n  - \"debug workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"root-cause diagnosis\"\n  - \"scoped repair workflow\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.1\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Debugging\n\nShared debugging workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure appears. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDebugging is the controlled experiment phase. It reproduces or tightly characterizes the symptom, captures exact evidence, traces the symptom backward to a source cause, applies one-cause fixes, and sends the result back through quality and verification.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Diagnosing a failing test, build failure, runtime exception, console error, broken interaction, layout regression, command failure, or inconsistent runtime behavior.\n- Recovering from failed implementation, failed quality, failed verification, or a concrete regression.\n- Tracing a symptom backward before changing code.\n- Applying a minimal bug fix to already-scoped files after the root cause is identified.\n- Dispatching a bounded parallel investigation when the search space is broad but the symptom is concrete.\n- Enforcing the three-strike escalation rule after repeated failed fixes for the same symptom.\n\n### When Not to Use\n\n- The work is planned implementation or refactoring without a failing symptom; use the implementation phase.\n- The work is an author-side quality gate with no concrete failing behavior; use the quality phase.\n- The work is final non-mutating evidence after a fix; use the verification phase.\n- The user wants findings-first review output rather than author-side repair.\n- The task is documentation-only prose with no failing behavior.\n\n---\n\n## 2. WORKFLOW\n\n### Debug Loop\n\n1. Resolve the active surface and lifecycle phase through shared references. If the surface is unknown, ask for runtime and verification commands before changing code.\n2. Reproduce the symptom. If it cannot be reproduced, collect the exact command, logs, inputs, state, or interaction steps needed to narrow it.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":50,"totalLines":121,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_debug.md","time":{"start":1783921533677,"end":1783921533681}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02bfd204f02fa561016a547b7d6c248191b5cbf0c3b37e6c7d"}},"id":"prt_f5a026270001Nd1zHHjZ78O8FL","sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","messageID":"msg_f5a0211520013lygw3ydBKV8sp"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921533722,"sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_bJkTyYbYVxj8zoLqRzCVad0P","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_implement.md","offset":1,"limit":50},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_implement.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Workflow Reference - Implementation\n3: description: Shared implementation workflow doctrine for sk-code — research and mutating build work run after the shared router resolves the active surface, consumed by every surface packet.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"sk-code implementation workflow\"\n6:   - \"implement workflow doctrine\"\n7:   - \"mutating build workflow\"\n8:   - \"surface implementation standards\"\n9: importance_tier: important\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 4.1.0.2\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Workflow Reference - Implementation\n15: \n16: Shared implementation workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers research and mutating build work after the shared router has resolved the active surface. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Implementation is the mutating build phase. It owns research before change, the smallest correct workspace edit, and the handoff into quality, debugging, and verification. It consumes surface identity from the shared router and then loads only the active surface resources needed for the task.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Writing, modifying, refactoring, or building code in the active surface.\n29: - Implementing a feature, script, component, module, fallback, parameter, authoring packet, or runtime behavior.\n30: - Researching unfamiliar, risky, config-sensitive, security-sensitive, or multi-file code before changing it.\n31: - Applying surface-specific authoring patterns after the active surface has already been resolved.\n32: - Consuming an animation or motion overlay as peer reference material after surface detection, not as a replacement for surface standards.\n33: \n34: ### When Not to Use\n35: \n36: - A concrete failing symptom is the dominant task; switch to debugging.\n37: - The implementation is already written and needs author-side P0/P1/P2 checks, comment hygiene, or surface checklists; proceed to quality.\n38: - The task is final non-mutating evidence; proceed to verification.\n39: - The user wants findings-first review output rather than workspace mutation.\n40: - The change is documentation-only prose with no executable behavior or routing change.\n41: \n42: ---\n43: \n44: ## 2. WORKFLOW\n45: \n46: ### Research\n47: \n48: Run research before changing unfamiliar or high-blast code. For simple localized edits, research can be brief, but it still includes reading the actual target file before writing.\n49: \n50: 1. Read the target files first; do not edit a file you have not read in this session.\n\n(Showing lines 1-50 of 125. Use offset=51 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Implementation\ndescription: Shared implementation workflow doctrine for sk-code — research and mutating build work run after the shared router resolves the active surface, consumed by every surface packet.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code implementation workflow\"\n  - \"implement workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"mutating build workflow\"\n  - \"surface implementation standards\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 4.1.0.2\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Implementation\n\nShared implementation workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers research and mutating build work after the shared router has resolved the active surface. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_implement.md","text":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Implementation\ndescription: Shared implementation workflow doctrine for sk-code — research and mutating build work run after the shared router resolves the active surface, consumed by every surface packet.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code implementation workflow\"\n  - \"implement workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"mutating build workflow\"\n  - \"surface implementation standards\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 4.1.0.2\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Implementation\n\nShared implementation workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers research and mutating build work after the shared router has resolved the active surface. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nImplementation is the mutating build phase. It owns research before change, the smallest correct workspace edit, and the handoff into quality, debugging, and verification. It consumes surface identity from the shared router and then loads only the active surface resources needed for the task.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Writing, modifying, refactoring, or building code in the active surface.\n- Implementing a feature, script, component, module, fallback, parameter, authoring packet, or runtime behavior.\n- Researching unfamiliar, risky, config-sensitive, security-sensitive, or multi-file code before changing it.\n- Applying surface-specific authoring patterns after the active surface has already been resolved.\n- Consuming an animation or motion overlay as peer reference material after surface detection, not as a replacement for surface standards.\n\n### When Not to Use\n\n- A concrete failing symptom is the dominant task; switch to debugging.\n- The implementation is already written and needs author-side P0/P1/P2 checks, comment hygiene, or surface checklists; proceed to quality.\n- The task is final non-mutating evidence; proceed to verification.\n- The user wants findings-first review output rather than workspace mutation.\n- The change is documentation-only prose with no executable behavior or routing change.\n\n---\n\n## 2. WORKFLOW\n\n### Research\n\nRun research before changing unfamiliar or high-blast code. For simple localized edits, research can be brief, but it still includes reading the actual target file before writing.\n\n1. Read the target files first; do not edit a file you have not read in this session.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":50,"totalLines":125,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_implement.md","time":{"start":1783921533714,"end":1783921533721}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02bfd204f02fa561016a547b7d6c348191b637d6aac84843c0"}},"id":"prt_f5a0262f9001fh449pITcDiv59","sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","messageID":"msg_f5a0211520013lygw3ydBKV8sp"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921533758,"sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Wfdcivv3cgXhFRy2paclcKL4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_verify.md","offset":1,"limit":50},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_verify.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Workflow Reference - Verification\n3: description: Shared verification workflow doctrine for sk-code — the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done/works/complete/fixed/passing/ready claim.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"sk-code verification workflow\"\n6:   - \"verify workflow doctrine\"\n7:   - \"falsifier discipline\"\n8:   - \"completion claim gate\"\n9: importance_tier: important\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 4.1.0.2\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Workflow Reference - Verification\n15: \n16: Shared verification workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Verification owns evidence, not fixes. It runs fresh surface-appropriate commands, records outcomes, compares against the implementation baseline, names blind spots, and claims only what the evidence proves. If verification fails, it hands back to debugging, implementation, or quality without editing.\n25: \n26: ### Iron Law\n27: \n28: **Iron Law** — make no completion claim without fresh surface-appropriate verification evidence. A clean static read is not runtime evidence, a green unit test is not live proof, a minified bundle is not browser interaction, and a browser click is not full regression coverage; name the rung and its blind spot.\n29: \n30: ### When to Use\n31: \n32: - Verifying work after implementation, quality checks, or debugging.\n33: - Running final commands before a done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim.\n34: - Collecting evidence for active-surface behavior or system-code changes.\n35: - Reporting the delta from the baseline captured before implementation.\n36: - Running mutation checks or claim-falsifier checks after a green result.\n37: - Walking the verification ladder and naming each rung's blind spot.\n38: \n39: ### When Not to Use\n40: \n41: - The task requires writing code, scaffolding files, or changing behavior; switch to implementation.\n42: - The task is author-side quality cleanup; use the quality phase.\n43: - Verification finds a defect that needs root-cause repair; switch to debugging.\n44: - The user wants findings-first review output or PR-style critique.\n45: - The active surface and verification command set are unknown; ask for them before claiming anything.\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## 2. WORKFLOW\n50: \n\n(Showing lines 1-50 of 175. Use offset=51 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Verification\ndescription: Shared verification workflow doctrine for sk-code — the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done/works/complete/fixed/passing/ready claim.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code verification workflow\"\n  - \"verify workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"falsifier discipline\"\n  - \"completion claim gate\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 4.1.0.2\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Verification\n\nShared verification workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_verify.md","text":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Verification\ndescription: Shared verification workflow doctrine for sk-code — the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done/works/complete/fixed/passing/ready claim.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code verification workflow\"\n  - \"verify workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"falsifier discipline\"\n  - \"completion claim gate\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 4.1.0.2\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Verification\n\nShared verification workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nVerification owns evidence, not fixes. It runs fresh surface-appropriate commands, records outcomes, compares against the implementation baseline, names blind spots, and claims only what the evidence proves. If verification fails, it hands back to debugging, implementation, or quality without editing.\n\n### Iron Law\n\n**Iron Law** — make no completion claim without fresh surface-appropriate verification evidence. A clean static read is not runtime evidence, a green unit test is not live proof, a minified bundle is not browser interaction, and a browser click is not full regression coverage; name the rung and its blind spot.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Verifying work after implementation, quality checks, or debugging.\n- Running final commands before a done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim.\n- Collecting evidence for active-surface behavior or system-code changes.\n- Reporting the delta from the baseline captured before implementation.\n- Running mutation checks or claim-falsifier checks after a green result.\n- Walking the verification ladder and naming each rung's blind spot.\n\n### When Not to Use\n\n- The task requires writing code, scaffolding files, or changing behavior; switch to implementation.\n- The task is author-side quality cleanup; use the quality phase.\n- Verification finds a defect that needs root-cause repair; switch to debugging.\n- The user wants findings-first review output or PR-style critique.\n- The active surface and verification command set are unknown; ask for them before claiming anything.\n\n---\n\n## 2. WORKFLOW\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":50,"totalLines":175,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_verify.md","time":{"start":1783921533754,"end":1783921533757}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02bfd204f02fa561016a547b7d6c488191b1a9cc6ab177b07e"}},"id":"prt_f5a026317001eGX63PKIpqMv1r","sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","messageID":"msg_f5a0211520013lygw3ydBKV8sp"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921533771,"sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vneBhvUoMhSXBiZMSbU5J3iE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md","offset":1,"limit":55},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Webflow CSS Quality Standards\"\n3: description: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow css quality standards\"\n6:   - \"will change management\"\n7:   - \"gpu accelerated properties\"\n8:   - \"css custom property prefix\"\n9:   - \"bem naming enforcement\"\n10:   - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n11:   - \"fluid typography webflow\"\n12: importance_tier: normal\n13: contextType: implementation\n14: version: 3.5.0.2\n15: ---\n16: \n17: # Webflow CSS Quality Standards\n18: \n19: > See [`../style_guide.md`](../style_guide.md) for CSS naming, custom property prefixes, attribute selectors, animation CSS, and file organization. See [`../../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for cross-language rules. This file covers CSS quality patterns AND CSS-specific enforcement.\n20: \n21: ---\n22: \n23: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n24: \n25: ### Purpose\n26: \n27: CSS quality patterns (will-change management, GPU acceleration, easing standards, fluid typography) plus the four CSS-specific enforcement subsections (custom property naming, attribute selector i flag, BEM, animation properties).\n28: \n29: ### When to Use\n30: \n31: - Validating CSS before claiming implementation complete\n32: - Fixing CSS violations identified by the code quality checklist\n33: - Setting up will-change cleanup or fluid-typography breakpoints\n34: \n35: ### Core Principle\n36: \n37: Defensive CSS patterns prevent runtime jank; explicit enforcement rules prevent silent regressions.\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: ## 2. CSS QUALITY PATTERNS\n42: \n43: ### will-change Management\n44: \n45: ```css\n46: /* Set will-change in JavaScript BEFORE animation starts */\n47: .animating {\n48:   will-change: transform, opacity;\n49: }\n50: \n51: /* Reset after animation completes (via JavaScript) */\n52: .animation-complete {\n53:   will-change: auto;\n54: }\n55: ```\n\n(Showing lines 1-55 of 307. Use offset=56 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow CSS Quality Standards\"\ndescription: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css quality standards\"\n  - \"will change management\"\n  - \"gpu accelerated properties\"\n  - \"css custom property prefix\"\n  - \"bem naming enforcement\"\n  - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n  - \"fluid typography webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow CSS Quality Standards\n\n> See [`../style_guide.md`](../style_guide.md) for CSS naming, custom property prefixes, attribute selectors, animation CSS, and file organization. See [`../../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for cross-language rules. This file covers CSS quality patterns AND CSS-specific enforcement.\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow CSS Quality Standards\"\ndescription: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css quality standards\"\n  - \"will change management\"\n  - \"gpu accelerated properties\"\n  - \"css custom property prefix\"\n  - \"bem naming enforcement\"\n  - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n  - \"fluid typography webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow CSS Quality Standards\n\n> See [`../style_guide.md`](../style_guide.md) for CSS naming, custom property prefixes, attribute selectors, animation CSS, and file organization. See [`../../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for cross-language rules. This file covers CSS quality patterns AND CSS-specific enforcement.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nCSS quality patterns (will-change management, GPU acceleration, easing standards, fluid typography) plus the four CSS-specific enforcement subsections (custom property naming, attribute selector i flag, BEM, animation properties).\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Validating CSS before claiming implementation complete\n- Fixing CSS violations identified by the code quality checklist\n- Setting up will-change cleanup or fluid-typography breakpoints\n\n### Core Principle\n\nDefensive CSS patterns prevent runtime jank; explicit enforcement rules prevent silent regressions.\n\n---\n\n## 2. CSS QUALITY PATTERNS\n\n### will-change Management\n\n```css\n/* Set will-change in JavaScript BEFORE animation starts */\n.animating {\n  will-change: transform, opacity;\n}\n\n/* Reset after animation completes (via JavaScript) */\n.animation-complete {\n  will-change: auto;\n}\n```","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":55,"totalLines":307,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md","time":{"start":1783921533766,"end":1783921533770}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02bfd204f02fa561016a547b7d6c5881919673e77633451256"}},"id":"prt_f5a02633b001uWs1GVGXv0h1br","sessionID":"ses_0a6050609ffeLmwfdMHnBWCS8d","messageID":"msg_f5a0211520013lygw3ydBKV8sp"}}
